’Art Sociologique shared an opposition to institutional hegemony by adapting their works to unconventional spaces and audiences, asserting artistic autonomy from art institutions, and embracing interdisciplinarity. In showing how these artists used art to question what art should be and where it should be seen, Woodruff demonstrates how artists challenged and redefined the art establishment and their historical moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArt criticismxHistoryy20th centuryzFrance. 0aArt criticismzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aArt, FrenchxGovernment policyzFrance. 0aArts and societyzFrance. 0aArts, Moderny20th century. 0aGroupe de recherche d'art visuel. 0aInteractive artzFrance. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147801208540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012085/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles